03991nam a22004695i 9780773596351DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735963517 a10.1515/97807735963512doi  a(DE-B1597)654590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a942.0520922231 aJenkins, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLord Lyons :bA Diplomat in an Age of Nationalism and War /cBrian Jenkins. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tBeginnings -- tRome -- tEnvoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary -- tThe United States -- tThe Disunited States -- tThe American Civil War -- tCrisis -- tIntervention? -- tMarking Time -- tAmbassador to the Sublime Porte -- tTo the Diplomatic Summit -- tAmbassador to a Liberalizing Empire -- tThe Fall of the Second Empire -- tMonarchy or Republic? -- tThe Third Republic -- tEndings -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe British ambassador in Washington during the US Civil War and ambassador in Paris before and after the Franco-Prussian war, Lord Lyons (1817-1887) was one of the most important diplomats of the Victorian period. Although frequently featured in histories of the United States and Europe in the second half of the nineteenth century, and in discussions and analyses of British foreign policy, he has remained an ill-defined figure. In Lord Lyons: A Diplomat in an Age of Nationalism and War, Brian Jenkins explains the man and examines his career. Based on a staggering study of primary sources, he presents a convincing portrait of a subject who rarely revealed himself personally. Though he avoided publicity, Lyons came to be regarded as his nation's premier diplomat as his career took him to the heart of the great international issues and crises of his generation. As minister to the United States he played a vital role in preserving Anglo-American peace and was a powerful voice opposing Anglo-French intervention in the Civil War. While ambassador to the Ottoman Empire, he helped to prevent French control of the Suez Canal then under construction. In France, he maintained an amiable and constructive relationship with a bitter nation struggling to reorganize itself and its constitution after the Franco-Prussian War. For many historians Lord Lyons has been difficult to ignore but hard to admire. In rescuing him as a truly important historical figure, Jenkins details for the first time the personal and public strategies Lyons employed through decades of exemplary diplomatic service on both sides of the Atlantic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDiplomatic and consular service, BritishxHistoryy19th century. 0aDiplomatszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aFranco-Prussian War, 1870-1871xDiplomatic history. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359635140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773596351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773596351/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles